data.content:
**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** Both work exactly as you'd expect:

```csharp
Span<nint>  nints  = stackalloc nint[5];
Span<nuint> nuints = stackalloc nuint[3];
```

On this 64-bit system each `nint`/`nuint` is 8 bytes. The only gotcha is that `sizeof(nint)` requires an `unsafe` context (since the size isn't a compile-time constant), but `stackalloc` itself works fine in safe code when assigned to a `Span<T>`.
